  "riddle": "1. Begin your journey in the heart of a town known for its local governance—how many residents called this place home according to the census in 2011? \n\n2. Discover a hidden treasure; what is the next prime number after the total of the inhabitants you just uncovered?\n\n3. A page exists where you can learn about the governing bodies of rural areas—how many primary divisions does this article reveal in its table of contents?\n\n4. Venture onward to a revered site devoted to a deity atop a majestic hill—what is the latitude of this temple, measured in decimal degrees?\n\n5. Seek out a place of worship known for its unique philosophy—how many language representations does its article indicate are available at the top?\n\n6. Encounter the renowned figure in spirituality whose height aims to touch the heavens—how tall is this titan, measured in both feet and meters?\n\n7. Trace the roots of a beloved sweet treat; where did this delicacy originate according to its entry? \n\n8. Beyond local confectioneries, seek the tall land beneath the sun—what is the elevation of the subcontinent that hosts this delightful cuisine?\n\n9. While marveling at this vast expanse, how many museums can be found in the vicinity of this sprawling territory?\n\n10. From the heights to the culture, take the absolute difference between the elevation you found in clue 8 and the galleries you unearthed in clue 9.\n\n11. Further your exploration of knowledge by inquiring about centers of higher learning—how many universities are located nearby?\n\n12. As you journey, consider the origins of that sweet treat—what numerical position in the alphabet does its initial letter occupy?\n\n13. Expand your view to the expanse of a nation; what is the population of this land, known for its diversity and grandeur?\n\n14. For your final task, compute the following: what is the result when you take the sum of the answers from clues 2, 4, 8, and 10, and find the remainder when divided by 10? This will yield a single digit, which completes your quest!",
